<div class="wrap">

  <header class="reveal">
    <div class="kbd">Field&nbsp;notes <span class="dot">·</span> inside the Claude Code source</div>
    <h1>Your terminal is a <em>DOM</em>.<br>Claude Code paints it like a screen.<span class="cur"></span></h1>
    <p class="standfirst">Underneath, your terminal has nodes, a tree and text leaves — the same shape as a browser's DOM. Claude Code lays that tree into a grid of cells and sends only what changed to your screen, as escape codes. Here's how, with the code that does it.</p>
    <div class="byline">By <b style="color:var(--soft)">Royi Namir</b> · how Claude Code paints its interface · 6 min read</div>
  </header>

  <section class="reveal" style="animation-delay:.08s">
    <p style="font-size:20px">A line of output in Claude Code looks like ordinary <span class="mono">stdout</span>. It isn't. Behind it runs a small rendering engine that models your terminal as a <strong>two-dimensional grid of cells</strong>, lays an element tree into that grid, compares it to the previous frame, and sends your terminal only the cells that changed — as raw escape sequences. Let's follow a frame from memory to glowing phosphor.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="callout reveal" style="animation-delay:.06s">
    <span class="ic">📁</span>
    <p>Everything in this article — the cell buffer, the element tree, the frame diff, the hit-test — is pulled <b>straight from the Claude Code source code</b>. These are the real types and functions behind the interface you use every day.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- 1. THE GRID OF CELLS -->
  <section class="reveal" style="animation-delay:.04s">
    <span class="tag">step 1 · the buffer</span>
    <h2>Your screen is a grid of cells</h2>
    <p>The engine never thinks in "lines of text." It thinks in cells — one per character position on your screen. Each cell knows its glyph, its styling, how many columns it occupies, and whether it's a link:</p>

    <div class="panel">
      <div class="bar"><span class="dots"><i class="d-r"></i><i class="d-y"></i><i class="d-g"></i></span><span class="file"><b>screen.ts</b> — one cell</span></div>
<pre><span class="c">// every character on screen is one Cell</span>
<span class="k">type</span> <span class="t">Cell</span> = {
  <span class="pn">char</span>:      <span class="a">string</span>      <span class="c">// the glyph: "C" — or even "🖥"</span>
  <span class="pn">styleId</span>:   <span class="a">number</span>      <span class="c">// color · bold · underline (interned)</span>
  <span class="pn">width</span>:     <span class="t">CellWidth</span>   <span class="c">// 1 column — or 2 for wide glyphs</span>
  <span class="pn">hyperlink</span>?: <span class="a">string</span>      <span class="c">// yes: a cell can be a link</span>
}</pre>
    </div>

    <p>And the whole screen isn't an array of those objects — that would mean tens of thousands of allocations every frame. It's one flat block of integers, the way a GPU holds a framebuffer:</p>

    <div class="panel">
      <div class="bar"><span class="dots"><i class="d-r"></i><i class="d-y"></i><i class="d-g"></i></span><span class="file"><b>screen.ts</b> — the framebuffer</span></div>
<pre><span class="c">// the whole screen is one typed array — no objects, no GC</span>
<span class="c">// 2 × Int32 per cell:  [ charId ][ styleId | linkId | width ]</span>
<span class="k">const</span> <span class="n">buf</span>   = <span class="k">new</span> <span class="fn">ArrayBuffer</span>(size <span class="pn">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class="s">3</span>)   <span class="c">// 8 bytes / cell</span>
<span class="k">const</span> <span class="n">cells</span> = <span class="k">new</span> <span class="fn">Int32Array</span>(buf)</pre>
    </div>
    <p>That's the surface Claude Code paints onto: a packed grid of integers it can scan and compare at memory speed.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- 2. THE ELEMENT TREE -->
  <section class="reveal" style="animation-delay:.04s">
    <span class="tag">step 2 · the layout</span>
    <h2>The UI is an element tree — a DOM, for the terminal</h2>
    <p>What gets painted into those cells is decided by a tree of elements. If you've used a browser's developer tools, the shape is uncanny: nodes with a <span class="mono">nodeName</span>, <span class="mono">childNodes</span>, a <span class="mono">parentNode</span> — and real <span class="mono">#text</span> nodes at the leaves. Only the tag names give away that it's a terminal:</p>

    <div class="panel">
      <div class="bar"><span class="dots"><i class="d-r"></i><i class="d-y"></i><i class="d-g"></i></span><span class="file"><b>dom.ts</b> — a terminal DOM</span></div>
<pre><span class="k">type</span> <span class="t">ElementNames</span> =
  | <span class="s">"ink-root"</span> | <span class="s">"ink-box"</span> | <span class="s">"ink-text"</span> | <span class="s">"ink-link"</span>

<span class="k">type</span> <span class="t">DOMElement</span> = {
  <span class="pn">nodeName</span>:   <span class="t">ElementNames</span>
  <span class="pn">childNodes</span>: <span class="t">DOMNode</span>[]
  <span class="pn">parentNode</span>: <span class="t">DOMElement</span> | <span class="k">undefined</span>
}</pre>
    </div>

    <p>You describe this tree once; a <strong>flexbox</strong> layout engine then assigns every node a rectangle — a range of rows and columns. The little box of green text you see on screen is just the visible face of that tree:</p>

    <div class="panel">
      <div class="seevs">
        <div class="col">
          <div class="lbl">on your terminal</div>
          <div class="screenbox"><span class="g">Claude</span><br><span class="w">How can I help?</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="col">
          <div class="lbl">the tree underneath</div>
<pre style="padding:0;font-size:12.5px"><span class="k">ink-box</span>
<span class="c">├─</span> <span class="k">ink-text</span> <span class="c">→</span> <span class="t">#text</span> <span class="s">"Claude"</span>
<span class="c">└─</span> <span class="k">ink-text</span> <span class="c">→</span> <span class="t">#text</span> <span class="s">"How…"</span></pre>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FLOW -->
  <section class="reveal" style="animation-delay:.04s">
    <span class="tag">the pipeline</span>
    <h2>One frame, from memory to your screen</h2>
    <p>Put it together and every refresh runs the same short assembly line — the same shape a browser uses to paint a web page, ending at your terminal instead of a monitor:</p>

    <div class="panel">
      <div class="bar"><span class="file">a single frame</span></div>
      <div class="flow">
        <div class="spine"></div>
        <div class="stage"><div class="node">🌳</div><div class="body"><h4>Element tree</h4><p>A tree of <code>ink-box</code> / <code>ink-text</code> / <code>#text</code> nodes describes the UI.</p></div></div>
        <div class="stage"><div class="node">📐</div><div class="body"><h4>Flexbox layout</h4><p>Every node is assigned a rectangle of rows &amp; columns.</p></div></div>
        <div class="stage"><div class="node">🧱</div><div class="body"><h4>Painted into the cell grid</h4><p>Each node writes its glyphs + styles into the packed buffer.</p></div></div>
        <div class="stage"><div class="node">🔁</div><div class="body"><h4>Diffed vs. the last frame</h4><p>The engine finds the exact cells that changed.</p></div></div>
        <div class="stage"><div class="node">🎯</div><div class="body"><h4>Turned into escape codes</h4><p>Cursor moves + color + glyph — only for changed cells.</p></div></div>
        <div class="stage"><div class="node">⌨️</div><div class="body"><h4>Your terminal draws it</h4><p>The bytes hit <code>stdout</code>; the terminal renders the diff.</p></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 3. THE DIFF -->
  <section class="reveal" style="animation-delay:.04s">
    <span class="tag">step 3 · the diff</span>
    <h2>Only the cells that changed get sent</h2>
    <p>This is the heart of it — and why the UI never flickers. The engine doesn't reprint the screen. It walks the new grid against the old one and emits escape codes <em>only</em> where a cell actually changed:</p>

    <div class="panel">
      <div class="bar"><span class="dots"><i class="d-r"></i><i class="d-y"></i><i class="d-g"></i></span><span class="file"><b>log-update.ts</b> — frame diff → ANSI</span></div>
<pre><span class="c">// compare this frame's grid to the last one,</span>
<span class="c">// and touch ONLY the cells that differ</span>
<span class="fn">diffEach</span>(prevScreen, nextScreen, (x, y, before, after) <span class="k">=&gt;</span> {
  <span class="fn">emit</span>( <span class="fn">moveCursor</span>(x, y) )         <span class="c">//  ESC[&lt;row&gt;;&lt;col&gt;H</span>
  <span class="fn">emit</span>( <span class="fn">ansiColor</span>(after.styleId) ) <span class="c">//  ESC[32m …</span>
  <span class="fn">emit</span>( after.char )               <span class="c">//  the new glyph</span>
})</pre>
    </div>
    <p>Type one character and Claude Code might ship a dozen bytes, not a whole repaint. A spinner ticking next to a 2,000-line transcript touches only the spinner's cell.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- 4. WIDE CHARS -->
  <section class="reveal" style="animation-delay:.04s">
    <span class="tag">a terminal detail</span>
    <h2>Why emoji don't break the layout</h2>
    <p>Terminals are monospaced — until they aren't. An emoji or a CJK glyph is <em>two</em> columns wide, and getting that wrong shifts everything after it. So width is baked into every cell, with an explicit spacer for the column a wide glyph "leans into":</p>

    <div class="panel">
      <div class="bar"><span class="dots"><i class="d-r"></i><i class="d-y"></i><i class="d-g"></i></span><span class="file"><b>screen.ts</b> — cell width</span></div>
<pre><span class="k">const enum</span> <span class="t">CellWidth</span> {
  <span class="n">Narrow</span>     = <span class="s">0</span>,  <span class="c">// normal — 1 column</span>
  <span class="n">Wide</span>       = <span class="s">1</span>,  <span class="c">// CJK &amp; emoji — 2 columns</span>
  <span class="n">SpacerTail</span> = <span class="s">2</span>,  <span class="c">// the empty 2nd column it occupies</span>
}</pre>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 5. CLICKS -->
  <section class="reveal" style="animation-delay:.04s">
    <span class="tag">step 4 · input</span>
    <h2>When you click, the terminal sends a (col, row)</h2>
    <p>Mouse support in a terminal is just bytes too: a click arrives as a column and a row. To know <em>what</em> you clicked, the engine hit-tests that coordinate against the same tree — deepest match wins, and later siblings (drawn on top) are checked first:</p>

    <div class="panel">
      <div class="bar"><span class="dots"><i class="d-r"></i><i class="d-y"></i><i class="d-g"></i></span><span class="file"><b>hit-test.ts</b> — find what was clicked</span></div>
<pre><span class="k">function</span> <span class="fn">hitTest</span>(node, col, row) {
  <span class="k">const</span> r = node.rect
  <span class="k">if</span> (col <span class="pn">&lt;</span> r.x <span class="pn">||</span> col <span class="pn">&gt;=</span> r.x + r.width)  <span class="k">return</span> <span class="k">null</span>
  <span class="k">if</span> (row <span class="pn">&lt;</span> r.y <span class="pn">||</span> row <span class="pn">&gt;=</span> r.y + r.height) <span class="k">return</span> <span class="k">null</span>

  <span class="c">// later siblings paint on top → check them first</span>
  <span class="k">for</span> (<span class="k">let</span> i = node.childNodes.length - <span class="s">1</span>; i <span class="pn">&gt;=</span> <span class="s">0</span>; i--) {
    <span class="k">const</span> hit = <span class="fn">hitTest</span>(node.childNodes[i], col, row)
    <span class="k">if</span> (hit) <span class="k">return</span> hit
  }
  <span class="k">return</span> node
}</pre>
    </div>
    <p>That's how a button or a link in Claude Code knows it was the thing under your cursor — the exact algorithm a browser uses for <span class="mono">elementFromPoint</span>.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- 6. ESCAPE TRICKS -->
  <section class="reveal" style="animation-delay:.04s">
    <span class="tag">the escape-code tricks</span>
    <h2>Two things your terminal already knew how to do</h2>
    <p>Some effects aren't drawn at all — they're spoken to the terminal in its own language. A clickable link is one escape sequence wrapped around text (<strong>OSC 8</strong>):</p>

    <div class="panel">
      <div class="bar"><span class="file"><b>links</b> — OSC 8</span></div>
<pre><span class="k">const</span> OSC = <span class="s">"\x1b]"</span>, BEL = <span class="s">"\x07"</span>
<span class="k">const</span> link = <span class="s">`</span>${OSC}<span class="s">8;;</span>${url}${BEL}<span class="s">`</span> + text + <span class="s">`</span>${OSC}<span class="s">8;;</span>${BEL}<span class="s">`</span></pre>
    </div>

    <p>And scrolling a long transcript doesn't repaint every row — it hands the terminal a <strong>scroll region</strong> (DECSTBM) and asks it to shift its own rows, the closest thing a terminal has to hardware acceleration:</p>

    <div class="panel">
      <div class="bar"><span class="file"><b>scroll</b> — DECSTBM</span></div>
<pre><span class="fn">emit</span>(<span class="s">`\x1b[</span>${top}<span class="s">;</span>${bottom}<span class="s">r`</span>)   <span class="c">// set the scroll region</span>
<span class="fn">emit</span>(<span class="s">`\x1b[</span>${n}<span class="s">S`</span>)               <span class="c">// scroll up n rows — in hardware</span></pre>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FULL EXAMPLE -->
  <section class="reveal" style="animation-delay:.04s">
    <span class="tag">the full picture</span>
    <h2>One word, all the way to the screen</h2>
    <p>Here's every stage at once — the journey of a single word, <span class="mono">Claude</span>, in green and bold, from a node in the tree to the exact bytes your terminal receives:</p>

    <div class="panel">
      <div class="bar"><span class="dots"><i class="d-r"></i><i class="d-y"></i><i class="d-g"></i></span><span class="file">worked example — render <b>"Claude"</b></span></div>
<pre><span class="c">GOAL · put "Claude" (green + bold) in the top-left corner</span>

<span class="a">①  the element tree</span>
    <span class="k">ink-box</span>
    <span class="c">└─</span> <span class="k">ink-text</span>  <span class="pn">{</span> color: <span class="s">"green"</span>, bold <span class="pn">}</span>
       <span class="c">└─</span> <span class="t">#text</span>  <span class="s">"Claude"</span>

<span class="a">②  layout gives it a rectangle</span>  <span class="c">(rows × columns)</span>
    <span class="k">ink-text</span> <span class="c">→</span> <span class="pn">{</span> x: <span class="s">0</span>, y: <span class="s">0</span>, width: <span class="s">6</span>, height: <span class="s">1</span> <span class="pn">}</span>

<span class="a">③  painted into six cells — all sharing one styleId</span>
    <span class="c">┌────┬────┬────┬────┬────┬────┐</span>
    <span class="c">│</span> <span class="s">C</span>  <span class="c">│</span> <span class="s">l</span>  <span class="c">│</span> <span class="s">a</span>  <span class="c">│</span> <span class="s">u</span>  <span class="c">│</span> <span class="s">d</span>  <span class="c">│</span> <span class="s">e</span>  <span class="c">│</span>   <span class="c">← bold + green</span>
    <span class="c">└────┴────┴────┴────┴────┴────┘</span>

<span class="a">④  diff vs. last frame</span>  <span class="c">— row 0 was blank → all six cells are new</span>

<span class="a">⑤  written to stdout as one short burst of bytes:</span>
    <span class="t">\x1b[1;1H</span> <span class="t">\x1b[1m</span> <span class="t">\x1b[32m</span> <span class="s">Claude</span> <span class="t">\x1b[0m</span>
    <span class="c">└ cursor→1,1 └ bold  └ green   └ text  └ reset</span>

<span class="a">⑥  your terminal draws:</span>  <span class="s" style="font-weight:700">Claude</span></pre>
    </div>
    <p>That last line is the whole trick in one breath: a cursor jump, two colour codes, six letters, a reset — and not a single other cell on your screen is touched.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- KICKER -->
  <section class="reveal" style="animation-delay:.04s">
    <span class="tag">the takeaway</span>
    <h2>A screen, not a printer</h2>
    <blockquote>Claude Code doesn't write <b>to</b> your terminal. It treats it as a <b>display</b> — and runs a real rendering engine against it.</blockquote>
    <p>A grid of cells, a layout pass, a frame diff, a stream of escape codes, mouse hit-testing on a coordinate. None of it is exotic on its own — it's just a pipeline nobody expects to find behind a command-line tool. The constraints of a terminal turned out to be far softer than everyone assumed.</p>
